1. Recap: Bug bei der Mean Berechnung ("falsche" Koef.-Matrix)

  • Spezifizierte Basis und tatschlich geschtzte Basis unterscheiden sich bei der Verwendung von mgcv.
  • mgcv nimmt die spezifizierte Basis und implementiert noch einen "sum-to-one" constraint. Die ausgegebenen Koeffizienten gehren zur constrainten Basis.
  • Die "richtigen" Koeffizienten mssen ber entsprechende Basis-Trafo DD aus den constrainten Koeffizienten rekonstruiert werden: ^=D^~^=D~^.
  • DD wird leider nicht von mgcv mitgeliefert sondern muss extra berechnet werden ber X=D~XX=DX~, mit X,~XX,X~ Design- und constrained Designmatrix.

Ergebnisse sehen jetzt deutlich besser aus. Vor allem auch fr hhere Penalties! :)

2. Smooth Procrustes Fits

^p(t)=b(t)T^p^(t)=b(t)T^ estimated Procrustes mean function, qq piecewise constant SRV transform with q|[tj,tj+1]=qjCq|[tj,tj+1]=qjC.

For estimation of the Procrustes fits we need to estimate two scalar products:

^qp=q,^pq,qqq^p=q,p^q,qq

2.1 Piecewise constant approximation

So far I treat qq as piecewise constant (as in Lisa's paper):

q,^p=10q(t),^p(t)dtm1j=0tj+1tjqj,^p(t)dtq,p^=01q(t),p^(t)dtj=0m1tjtj+1qj,p^(t)dtq,q=10q(t),q(t)dtm1j=0(tj+1tj)qj,qjq,q=01q(t),q(t)dtj=0m1(tj+1tj)qj,qj

2.2 Smooth approximation

Idea: Smooth qq in mean basis b(t)b(t), so that ^q(t)=b(t)T^qq^(t)=b(t)T^q. Then the scalar products simplify to q,^p^HqG^q,p^^qHG^ q,q^HqG^qq,q^qHG^q

As qq can be sparse, we may want to use the estimated covariance matrix ^^ when estimating qq in the form of a Normal prior qNCk(0,^)qNCk(0,^) leading to

^q=(BTB+1)1BTq^q=(BTB+1)1BTq

or equivalently using eigendecompositon =VV1=VV1 with VHV=IVHV=I and =diag(1,,k)=diag(1,,k)

^q=V(VHBTBV+1)1VHBTq^q=V(VHBTBV+1)1VHBTq

In general how well this works tends to depend on how close the curve is to the estimated mean.

Maybe using a penalty parameter - controling the strength of the regularization - is also thinkable? Something like this:

^q()=V(VHBTBV+1)1VHBTq^q()=V(VHBTBV+1)1VHBTq

Thought: A normal prior is probably not appropriate, because while its true that E[]=0E[]=0 (due to rotational symmetry) I would think that in general E[]0E[]0. A distribution more like a Normal distribution lying on a ring around 0 with radius r=r= is probably better? Then estimates wouldn't be pressed to zero so strongly, and instead would be pressed to curve of size equal to the mean.

3. Closed means

Mean p(t)=b(t)Tp(t)=b(t)T with b(t)b(t) being B-spline basis functions with corresponding Gram matrix GG.

Then the procrustes mean in an orthogonal basis is the solution to optimization problem:

^=argmaxCkHG^Gs.t.HG=1^=argmaxCkHG^Gs.t.HG=1

For a closed mean, we additionally want that ||^(1)^(0)||2=0||^(1)^(0)||2=0. We can rewrite this on SRV level as

^(1)^(0)2=10^p(t)^p(t)dt2^(1)^(0)2=01p^(t)p^(t)dt2

It would be nice to write this restriction as a function of . Maybe like this?

10b(t)Tb(t)Tdt2??DU,b(t)010b(t)Tb(t)Tdt2=10Tb(t)b(t)Tdt2=T10b(t)b(t)Tdt201b(t)Tb(t)Tdt2??DU,b(t)001b(t)Tb(t)Tdt2=01Tb(t)b(t)Tdt2=T01b(t)b(t)Tdt2=TG2=TG2=HGTG=TG2=TG2=HGTG

Maybe the term TT can be simplified or bound from above further?

With estimated coefficient matrix ^^, so that ^C(s,t)=b(s)T^b(t)C^(s,t)=b(s)T^b(t) is closed, we end up with the optimization problem for the closed mean:

^=argmaxCkHG^Gs.t.HG=1andHGTG=0^=argmaxCkHG^Gs.t.HG=1andHGTG=0
